-- Bank Handlowy, Zachodni, PKO Bank May Move: Central Europe Stock Preview
-- Maciej Martewicz
-- 2010-06-28T06:22:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-28/bank-handlowy-zachodni-pko-bank-may-move-central-europe-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in central European
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names.
Share prices are from the last close.  
 Poland’s  WIG20 Index  gained 0.5 percent, the Czech  PX Index 
fell 0.6 percent and Hungary’s  BUX Index  dropped 2.3 percent.  
 Enea SA  (ENA PW): Poland called for bids for a majority
stake in the country’s third-largest utility, as the Treasury
Ministry continues selling power assets to help cover the budget
deficit. Enea rose 0.2 percent to 17.84 zloty.  
 Bank Handlowy SA  (BHW PW): Shareholders of the Polish unit
of Citigroup Inc. vote on a management proposal to pay a 2009
dividend of 3.77 zloty ($1.13) a share. Handlowy declined 2
percent to 72.5 zloty.  
 Bank Zachodni WBK SA  (BZW PW): Investors seeking to buy
Allied Irish Banks Plc’s 70 percent stake in the Polish lender
have a June 28 deadline to submit initial bids.  
 Allied Irish plans to shortlist bidders by mid-July and
complete the sale in September, the Rzeczpospolita newspaper
said, citing unnamed people familiar with the transaction.
Zachodni rose 0.8 percent to 194 zloty.  
 Monday Development SA  (MDV PW): The Polish property
developer will start trading on the Warsaw Stock Exchange’s
NewConnect market for smaller companies.  
 PKO Bank Polski SA  (PKO PW): The supervisory board of
Poland’s largest lender approved preparing an initial bid to buy
Bank Zachodni, Rzeczpospolita reported on June 26, without
citing anyone. PKO shares rose 1.3 percent to 38.25 zloty.  
